    <a title="J.L.   Sutton" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3675162-j-l-sutton"><img alt="J.L.   Sutton" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1438142892p2/3675162.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2605247932?book_show_action=true">Feb 03, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J.L.   Sutton" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J.L.   Sutton" href="/user/show/3675162-j-l-sutton">J.L.   Sutton</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2605247932" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10382204203483686051"><img alt='Image result for ballard drowned world' src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1583348806i/29056793._SX540_.jpg' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>The Drowned World is my first JG Ballard novel, but it won&apos;t be my last. Civilization is swallowed up by encroaching oceans. The lavish scenes of nature reclaiming the world belie the apocalyptic overtones. Life is shown adapting to a period on earth comparable to the Triassic Period. That is, all forms of life (including plants) adapt to the changing world except for man. People seem out of place even alien in the newly formed landscapes. De-evolved nature is inhospitable to man; it feels like </span>
  <span id="freeText10382204203483686051" style="display:none"><img alt="Image result for ballard drowned world" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1583348806i/29056793._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>The Drowned World is my first JG Ballard novel, but it won't be my last. Civilization is swallowed up by encroaching oceans. The lavish scenes of nature reclaiming the world belie the apocalyptic overtones. Life is shown adapting to a period on earth comparable to the Triassic Period. That is, all forms of life (including plants) adapt to the changing world except for man. People seem out of place even alien in the newly formed landscapes. De-evolved nature is inhospitable to man; it feels like man is being kicked out of paradise, but now with nowhere to go. Aspects of this book reminded me of Annihilation, but I'm sure I could find lots of novels influenced by Ballard's work. Not sure which Ballard novel to read next, but they'll make it onto my to-read list soon. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10382204203483686051" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
